This paper focuses on the problem of ranking design ideas based on both quality and diversity, which is a common problem in human-computer interaction (HCI) and information retrieval (IR) research. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). The paper also uses text-based measures and algorithms, which are common in natural language processing (NLP) and computational linguistics (CL), making cs.IR (Information Retrieval) and cs.CL (Computation and Language) likely categories as well. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of multi-objective optimization and trade-off fronts, which are relevant to the fields of cybernetics (cs.CY) and social and information networks (cs.SI).
